@recycledx

I'm afraid that the code is too complicated for you, and you can't understand it. If you really believe that results on the web page is correct is your problem.

My request is only for stuff.

@Juan

Look at this:

c = preyPred[0] * (1 + a[0] - a[1] * preyPred[1]);
r = preyPred[1] * (1 - b[0] + b[1] * preyPred[0]);
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
x = c * (1 + a[0] - a[1] * r);
double temp = x;
x = c;
c = temp;             
z = r * (1 - b[0] + b[1] * c);
double tmp = z;
z = r;
r = tmp;
}

Result of first equation x = ...  is argument for next period, swapping to "c" and use it like argument for x equation again and again for n times. This will get the proper result because it can use the proper values anytime. For z equation is same story.

Hi again, ugabrielu,

Your code:

      c = preyPred[0] * (1 + a[0] - a[1] * preyPred[1]);
      r = preyPred[1] * (1 - b[0] + b[1] * preyPred[0]);
      for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        x = c * (1 + a[0] - a[1] * r);
        double temp = x;
        x = c;
        c = temp;
        z = r * (1 - b[0] + b[1] * c);
        double tmp = z;
        z = r;
        r = tmp;
      }

First of all, at the beginning, before entering the loop, 'c' and 'r' already contain the value for 1 period. The next results will be off by one: when computing for '`n = 1`', you are actually computing for '`n = 2`'.

Second, what's the point of having so many temporary variables?

My fix (I didn't test it):

      c = preyPred[0];
      r = preyPred[1];
      for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        x = c * (1 + a[0] - a[1] * r);
        r = r * (1 - b[0] + b[1] * c);
        c = x;
      }
